mis_free: Just as with a flame, there is an inherent danger in the presence of a populist. A fire with enough heat and power to burn away the corruption and decay of a decadent administration can also burn far beyond the intended fields. Therefore, populism is not without risks. Take the French Revolution, for example. Is it possible that a new political reformation in the west could follow the same path, with one dynasty overthrown simply to be replaced by another once the old order of affairs breaks with the wave? Instability is the most common result\\This election has come down to the new face of populism vs. the old face of established corruption. Along with the possible third voice of an outsider joining the stage, both ideologically and politically speaking; although that as it stands is very unlikely.\\As such, populism is not constrained to the platform of the traditional American understanding of liberal, conservative, or libertarian.\\The message and appeal of a populist typically resonates more with the disenfranchised lower class. In the United States this class is, for the most part, fiscally liberal and socially conservative and possesses a distinct focus on national protectionism.\\The basic platform of such a populace can be summarized in only two words: America first. For other nations you need only to insert their country's name as the first word and that sums up any national populist platform currently in existence. (If one finds the term national to be unfavorable then patriotic can be substituted as watered down nationalism. Yet the meaning remains unchanged for the most part.)\\The parties claim to speak for the people, sometimes they go so far as to fashion themselves the benevolent laborer making great strides to better the masses. Reality, unfortunately, presents a less picturesque tale. The parties only speak for those who happen to share their particular platform and agenda, with no regard for those who don't.\\So what happens when millions of people find that no party shares their voice any more? Here is how the top three partisan organizations have done exactly that:\\The Democratic Party\\The Democratic Party platform has a strong focus on social progressive ideology and globalism, and is, therefore, rejected.\\The emphasis on environmentalism by the Democrats is especially damaging. It is easy to preach to an urban crowd to regulate large parts of the energy sector out of existence when most of their constituents have never seen a coal mine in their lives.\\However, this does not appeal to the forgotten industrial working class people who have, for generations, actually worked within the industries and enjoyed cheaper costs of energy in their areas. This is only to then see their factory or mine closed down and find themselves struggling in a now post-industrial society. It could well be said that they long for a restoration of that manufacturing based industrial society that once flourished in 20th century.\\The GOP\\The Republican Party platform has strong focus on fiscal conservatism, therefore, it is also rejected by the true populists on the basis that they simply do not want to make the major cuts needed to achieve a balanced budget; such as entitlement cuts and military cuts, while at the same time claiming not to want to raise taxes. Another major issue would be the aligning with Democratic whims when it comes to trade.\\The exception to this rule would be in the case of former/recent Republicans, where the rejection is mainly on the basis of a lack of faith in GOP leadership, rather than the party platform in itself. The difference between the two must be noted.

ideo_free: I consider to be the alt-right to be literally what it sounds like; an alternative to the typical right wing politics. It's kind of like a "punk rock," newer, hipper, less-establishment, less stuffy old-man, less Christian conservative version of the Republican party. Alt-righters are generally fiscal conservatives, socially moderate, and are mainly unified by the idea that the USA needs to take a step back and take care of itself instead of being so involved in, and influenced by, the global stage.
ident_free: Philosophically I tend to lean Libertarian, or perhaps what you might consider classical Liberal. I'm also an Atheist. I don't really fit in with traditional left or right, Democrat or Republican. Politicians whose beliefs align with my own simply don't have a whole lot of influence. I find a lot in common with the alt-right politically speaking; if I had to pick I lean more to the right/conservative/Republican realm, but really can't stand the Republican establishment, and also don't like the influence and emphasis of religion on the party politics. I believe our form of government is the greatest ever conceived and that we should pay more attention to the Constitution when it comes to governing. The idea of putting national interests in front of global interests resonates with me; not because I don't care about being a good global citizen, but I thinking looking inward and strengthening our position within actually puts us in a better position to achieve global goals. As political commentator Ann Coulter once put it - "America needs a little 'me' time right now."
mis_free: The big misconception is that the alt-right is made up of racists, anti-semites, sexists, homophobes - all sorts of "ists" and "isms." I don't doubt there are some alt-righters who are some of those things; you can find them in any group, but I think that's exaggerated and over-represented in the media. I also think there are others who take up that mantle and "troll" - and some reprehensible people who have tried to hijack their own little corners of the movement. People like that - the Richard Spencers etc aren't welcome by the vast majority within the alt-right, though they get all the attention. On the whole, we're just concerned Americans that wants what's best for our fellow Americans. I know many on the alt-right who genuinely care about improving race relations, who are perfectly tolerant of LGBT persons, and so on - often times more so than the traditional right. We really want the same things as everyone else, we just perhaps hold different ideas about how to go about it. A good example is the refugee crisis; alt-righters don't want an influx of refugees pouring into our country. It's not because we're racist or hate refugees (though it gets painted that way) - it's because our priority is keeping the peace within our own borders first and foremost, and secondly solving problems like a refugee crisis by fixing the situations that cause people to flee (i.e. establishing safe zones, or better yet, helping bring peace to areas like Syria) - the refugees would rather stay home themselves if it were safe, and everyone would be better off. So those are the sort of approaches we're often advocate for but is never really understood by the mainstream.
